𝐇𝐨𝐰 𝐋𝐢𝐧𝐮𝐱 𝐃𝐢𝐬𝐜𝐨𝐯𝐞𝐫𝐬 𝐘𝐨𝐮𝐫 𝐍𝐞𝐭𝐰𝐨𝐫𝐤 𝐂𝐚𝐫𝐝 𝐞1000 𝐃𝐫𝐢𝐯𝐞𝐫 𝐑𝐞𝐠𝐢𝐬𝐭𝐫𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐩𝐫𝐨𝐜𝐞𝐬𝐬. When you run insmod e1000.ko, a chain of events unfolds across hardware, firmware, and kernel layers.

LAYER 1: BIOS ENUMERATION (Power-On)

The BIOS scans every possible PCI address (256 buses × 32 devices × 8 functions) looking for devices.

For the Intel 82540EM at Bus 0, Device 3, Function 0:
- Writes 0xFFFFFFFF to BAR0, reads back 0xFFFE0000
- Size calculation: ~(0xFFFE0000) + 1 = 0x20000 (128 KB)
- Assigns: 0xf0200000, IRQ: 9

The NIC now responds to memory accesses at 0xf0200000–0xf021FFFF.

LAYER 2: KERNEL BOOT

Linux re-scans the entire bus via pci_scan_root_bus(). For each device, kernel creates struct pci_dev:

pci_dev {
 .vendor = 0x8086,  // Intel
 .device = 0x100E,  // 82540EM
 .devfn  = 0x18,  // (dev=3 << 3) | (func=0)
 .irq  = 9,   // From BIOS
 .resource[0] = {
 .start = 0xf0200000, // BAR0 start
 .end = 0xf021ffff, // BAR0 end (128KB)
 .flags = IORESOURCE_MEM,
 },
 .driver = NULL,  // ← NO DRIVER YET
}

LAYER 3: DRIVER REGISTRATION

The e1000 driver contains an ID match table:

pci_device_id e1000_pci_tbl[] = {
 ...
 { PCI_VDEVICE(INTEL, 0x100E), board_82540 }, ← THIS ONE
 // ... 80+
 { 0, }

When insmod e1000.ko executes:

e1000_init_module()
 └─ pci_register_driver(&e1000_driver)
  └─ driver_register()
   └─ For each pci_dev in global list:
     pci_bus_match(dev, &e1000_driver)

LAYER 4: THE MATCH

The kernel walked through e1000_pci_tbl[], comparing each entry against the discovered device. When it hit entry with vendor=0x8086 & device=0x100E → MATCH!

Now e1000_probe() callback fires.

LAYER 5: INSIDE e1000_probe()

STEP 1: Enable Device Memory Access

bars=0x5 = binary 0b101 = BARs 0 and 2
- BAR0: 128KB MMIO register space
- BAR2: I/O port fallback

Device powered to D0, INTX_DISABLE bit cleared.

STEP 2: Set Bus Master - THE CRITICAL BIT FLIP

This single bit grants DMA permission. Without it: NIC can only respond to CPU-initiated reads/writes, cannot initiate DMA autonomously, packets stuck, interface dead.

With bit 2 set, the NIC becomes a bus master & can autonomously read TX descriptors from RAM, DMA packet data, write RX descriptors, & DMA received packets directly to RAM.

STEP 3: Map Hardware Registers
Virtual 0xffffc9000021FFFF → Physical 0xf0200000–0xf021FFFF

STEP 4: Allocate Network Device
STEP 5: Hardware Reset & MAC Address
STEP 6: Register with Network Stack

VERIFICATION

$ lspci -xxx -s 00:03.0
00: 86 80 0e ...
10: 00 00 20 f0 00 00 ..

 BAR0 = 0xf0200000 (little-endian)

Driver binding confirmed:
$ cat /sys/bus/pci/devices/0000:00:03.0/driver
../../drivers/e1000 ← NOW BOUND ✓

When you run ip link set enp0s3 up, the kernel calls e1000_open(): allocates TX/RX rings (DMA memory), writes ring addresses to NIC registers, registers interrupt handler, enables interrupts, starts packet flow.

